[[File:Zero-curtain-effect.svg|thumb|Theoretical illustration of the zero-curtain effect over a 12-month period]]
The '''zero-curtain effect''' occurs in cold (particularly [[periglacial]]) environments where the [[phase transition]] of [[water]] to [[ice]] is slowed down due to [[latent heat]] release. The effect is notably found in [[arctic]] and [[alpine climate|alpine]] [[permafrost]] sediments, and occurs where the air temperature falls below 0'''°'''C (the [[freezing point]] of water) followed by a rapid drop in soil temperature.<ref>{{Cite journal| volume = 22| issue = 4| pages = 425–437| last = Kelley| first = J. J.|author2=D. F. Weaver | title = Physical processes at the surface of the arctic tundra| journal = Arctic| year = 1969| url = http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic22-4-425.pdf| doi=10.14430/arctic3233}}</ref>
Because of this effect, the lowering of temperature in moist, cold ground does not happen at a uniform rate. The loss of heat through conduction is reduced when water freezes, and latent heat is released. This heat of fusion is continually released until all the subsurface water has frozen, at which point temperatures can continue to fall.<ref>{{Cite journal| volume = 8| issue = 4| pages = 237–249| last = Cook| first = F. A| title = Near surface soil temperature measurements at Resolute Bay, Northwest Territories| journal = Arctic| year = 1955| url = http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/arctic8-4-237.pdf| doi=10.14430/arctic3822}}</ref>
Therefore, for as long as water is available to the system (for example, through [[cryosuction]]/[[capillary action]]) the temperature of the sediment will remain at a constant temperature.
